description.text:
I have Only designed this parts after seeing realms https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2603041 and decided i would like something to be glued a bit more sturdy on the fuselage and accommodate my motor choice.
I have not printed it or tested it yet and this specifically, has been designed on tinkercad and not autocad.

I will print it soon on a Prusa i3Mk2S on Z-Ultrat Material since when it comes to mechanical parts for me its the material of choice.

Hope someone else enjoys it too.
Update 07/12/2017:
All 4 parts have been printed and the variety of extended versions are to fit your needs on propeller air intake and also Wing balance since inside my wind there are alot of extras that give an all up weight close to 950gr.
Soon i will also post some Li-Ion battery spacers that are for the battery of this wind also as also a number of additional parts for the landing skid to protect.

First Layer at 260 and remaining layers at 268c
Bed temp for first is 90c and remaining is 95c while a cooling fan is set to auto from 20-30% speed.
The whole print is done in an enclosure that has a steady 30c ambient temperature.

comments.text:
I printed it with 100% infill, PLA, 215c head, 70c bed. very strong.
perfect fit to the Sonicmodell HD.
but I think the top is a little bit tall, so I stop at around 70%, this save a lot of weight.
and the screw hole is M3, since the hole is long, it hard to screw in, please make and upgrade version that has a larger screw hole that the M3 just go in without screwing.
comments.author: rcdavidng

comments.text:
Hello, my friend and thank you for the print and comment. The idea of the design was to have the F80 come out of the fuselage a bit in order to have the prop be able to get more air. In our build, we have a folding prop and so far printed 3 lengths to check which one gives best results.
On the design, the screw hole was 3.3mm which in theory should give you more than enough clearance. My test parts were printed on an Mk2S with Zortax Z-Ultrat filament to be able in case of emergency to hold under the motor temp. Even though the wing so far is to be tested only on how slow it will fly before stalling.

description.text:
I designed this to be used with the spare sensor that comes with the Tevo Tarantula kit. You can either use small screws (M2) to attach the switch, or as I do here, simply use 1.75mm filament to attach the switch to the enclosure. Screw the enclosure together with 3 M3 x 12mm screws and nuts. I used some short pieces of PTFE tubing on the ends of the enclosure, but this is by no means necessary.

Print the filament_runout_enclosure.stl twice. After printing you may want to sand the pieces down, so the fit together nice and flush.

I used the Z+ Port, therefore you need to set FIL_RUNOUT_PIN in pins_RAMPS.h to 19:

#define FIL_RUNOUT_PIN          19

In Configuration.h search for the FILAMENT_RUNOUT_SENSOR define and comment it out. If you want to use the default pinout, also invert the logic of the sensor and disable the internal pullup:

#define FILAMENT_RUNOUT_SENSOR
#if ENABLED(FILAMENT_RUNOUT_SENSOR)
  #define FIL_RUNOUT_INVERTING true // set to true to invert the logic of the sensor.
  //#define ENDSTOPPULLUP_FIL_RUNOUT // Uncomment to use internal pullup for 
filament runout pins if the sensor is defined.
  #define FILAMENT_RUNOUT_SCRIPT "M600"
#endif

More information about the Marlin configuration can be found here.

OpenSCAD file is attached and may be customized via Customizer in case you want to adapt it for a different switch, or your tolerances.

title: NASA Saturn V Stage 1 to 2 additional coupling ring

description.text:
If you enjoy any of my Things, please sponsor my charity cycle ride to Paris. https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/petethevanstp or text PTVC63 £5 to 70070 (UK number). Expires 1st May 2018. Thanks!

If you are thinking of printing the Saturn V from the NASA web site (from here https://nasa3d.arc.nasa.gov/detail/SATURNV) then I found it has an error (IMHO) in the model for Stage 2 at the base. The coupling ring model doesn't mate at all to the bottom of Stage 2. When you assemble the parts you get a 5mm gap (pic - I turned the coupler upside down just to illustrate the point, I'd already glued it on before doing this summary!).

I printed this extra ring which you glue onto the base of Stage 2.

Note that the ring fits just fine onto the coupling ring but the Stage 2 model itself is a slightly smaller diameter - so a little careful filing won't go amiss.

BIG NOTE: It's about 85mm in diameter and very thin - so take extra when cleaning up the raft etc.

FYI: There are 216 ridges around the ring...

Ring-to-Stage 2 leaves a gap. Glue the ring on Stage 2 Gap gone!

I grabbed the STL file for NASA's coupling ring and loaded it into Fusion 360. I used that as a template to draw two concentric circles the correct diameter (plus a small fit tolerance of about 0.3mm). Then I drew a triangle with the apex at the outer edge. This has sides 0.7mm and an angle of 89 deg. After that I using a repeating circular pattern of 216 triangles - this was found by trial-and-error until I got a fit over the original STL.

A two-part sanding block, with an acutely angled corner to reach into corners. The grip holds the sandpaper in place. The block is 115mm in length, the same width a sanding roll or half a sheet of sandpaper.

Step 1

You will need:
1x M5 x 40 screw (I used a panhead, but other may work with a washer)
1x M5 hex nut
1x M5 wing nut

Heat the hex nut on the end of a soldering iron, using the iron to place the nut into the hole in the base plate for a tight fit. The nut should be flush with the surface. Allow the nut and parts to cool before proceeding.

Step 2

Screw the M5 x 40 bolt (and washer, if using) in from the bottom of the base plate, through the nut you inserted in step one, until the head of the screw is beneath the surface of the part.
Place the hand grip over the protruding bolt and secure with the wing nut.

Step 3 (optional)

You may find it useful to flatten the bottom and angled surface of the base plate, to ensure that your sandpaper gives an even finish to your workpieces. To do this, put a piece of medium grit sandpaper on a flat surface (or better still a piece of flat glass) and move the part on top of it in a figure of 8 pattern, until the high spots have flattened out.
Design based on a commercially available sanding block, but adjusted to better fit the sanding roll you can purchase form many DIY shops at 115mm wide.

These parts are also likely to work with some of the other IKEA office chairs as I believe they re-use the same strut elsewhere; if it's got a 28mm strut inner, it'll probably fit.

The main "chair support" model will snap onto the strut and lock the height to nearly full.
I found this a bit much, so made a short version that locks it at half-height again. With both of these you can still merrily spin round on the chair as you wish.

Finally, the bushing is intended to be printed in flexible filament (I used PolyFlex at 20% infill) and provides a slight cushion. Perhaps. Totally optional, though.

title: WWII stealth plane, Horten 229, aircraft model kit

description.text:
Are you into plastic model kits? Do you like exotic planes? well, me too...
Here is my last project. It is an astounding piece of aircraft design, directly from the last days of the WW2 here you have the frame version (accurately replicated from the original blue prints) of HO-229. This plane never entered into service but two prototipes were built of its third version.One crashed during a test flight the second one was found in its hangar by the allied at the end of war. Nowdays it lies at the Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum. It seems that Northrop Grumman guys paid a visit at the museum before designing the famous stealth bomber B-2.
It is believed that, if deployed in quantity, the Ho 229 could have changed the course of war. Here you find all the parts (96) to build your Ho-229. you have to apply a scale factor of 35% in order to get a 1:30 model (570mm wingspan). Rev.1
added a zip file with all the parts.
what else... enjoy! printing is ongoing, more pics will come

  4. Made it compatible with original blower screws.
  5. The top screw is non accessible with the 20mm tall fan, I've narrowed down the hole and now I've placed the screw on a opposite direction just to prevent it from rotating.

title: Antenna Mast Mount for Elecraft T1 Tuner

description.text:
This mount allows attaching an Elecraft T1 antenna tuner directly to a portable antenna mast, e.g. a squid pole. You can thus keep the tuner directly at the feedpoint of a vertical antenna and do not have to use lossy feedline or lead the radiator wire end down to the ground.

Assembly: Simply insert a piece of elastic band (like the one used for tent poles) through one of the holes and tie a knot at the other end. The distance between the holes and the knot depends on the diameter of your smallest mast.

Use: Remove the ground/counterpoise knurled nut (not the simple nut below the knurled nut!) on top of the T1 tuner, attach the 3d-printed mount, and fasten the ground/counterpoise knurled nut again. It is really important to not loosen the simple nut directly at the T1 enclosure, because you will have to open the enclosure to tighten it again.

When attaching the T1 to your antenna mast, simply pull the rubber band around the rear side of the mast and let it slide into the right side of the mount. Use the position that fits best to the diameter of your mast.

Some masts have a very smooth surface that makes the mounting unreliable. In that case, you could either use regular rubber bands or apply liquid rubber to the surface of the mount.

Enjoy, and see you on the bands!

New hardware and software for Arduino Player Piano (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1174721)

Print list:

See https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1174721 for STL files

Required Components

Arduino Nano (You can use a Mini or UNO if you wish however the PCB is designed for a Nano)
12 5mm LEDs
14 10uF/16V low profile capacitors
12 Resistors with correct resistance for your LEDs
2 2N3904 or and other General Purpose NPN switching transistor eg: BC547
12 12mm Tactile Switches with button tops
1 Momentary (normally open) push button switch with 12mm diameter hole ( Example )
1 10k Resistor (For your switches)
2 1k Resistors (For your speakers)
1 0.1uF Capacitor (5mm hole spacing)
2 Speakers - 8ohm - low wattage - 30mm diameter ( Example )

Optional, you can use the USB connector on the Nano to supply power

1 Mini 3A DC-DC Adjustable Converter Step Down Power Supply (https://www.ebay.com/itm/5X-Mini-3A-DC-DC-Adjustable-Converter-Step-Down-Power-Supply-Replace-LM2596/172316993050?hash=item281ee4a61a:g:dr4AAOSwaB5XvR9u)
1 DC Power Jack Socket Connector PCB Mount 2.1*5.5 mm (https://www.ebay.com/itm/10PCS-DC-Power-Jack-Socket-Connector-PCB-Mount-2-1-5-5-mm/222528974958?epid=926115365&hash=item33cfc2b06e:g:dPIAAOSwIaFZLS~e)

Hardware changes:

Redesigned schematic to have the button and associated led share the same IO pin. This reduces the pin count required and allows the use of a smaller Arduino to be used.
Each switch (key) now has a simple RC network to provide hardware debouncing.
Added transistors to drive the speakers which provides protection to the Arduino.
Created PCBs to hold the LED, buttons, Arduino and other associated components in Eagle. (Files included).

Assembly:

Keyboard button holes need to be drilled out to fit keyboard button tops.
LED board screwed into back of organ. (I drilled 3mm holes in the PCB, 2.5mm holes in the piano and used a 3mm tap to create a thread. Used M3 x 8mm screws).
CPU board held in place using 12mm pillars.

Software:

Software has been rewritten to use another tone library.
The melodies have been moved from RAM to Flash memory so that it will fit in an Arduino Uno. Both the frequency and duration fixed length arrays have been combined into a single variable length array. This further reduces the memory footprint.
If you add more tunes, ensure that the last note in the array is END_OF_TUNE and the melodies array is updated to point to it. Other than playing different tunes, the software operates in the same manner as the original.

title: MagSDHolder

description.text:
Needed a SD card holder for my 3D printer and didn't see any that would work for me. I wanted at least a 4 SD card holder and wanted it to be easily removable if I moved my printer. There were a few designs that clipped over the edge of the door opening but would interfere with the door. SO I decided to start from scratch. The holder uses a rare earth magnet and simply sticks to the metal housing of the printer where ever I want to place it, this won't work on your printer if has a plastic, wood, or aluminum frame or housing to it.

I used some of the extra magnets I had from my GoPro Mag Mount
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1949608 that I designed. The link below is the site I got the magnets from but any 15mm x 5mm magnet will work. I used them because I had extras and also being rare earth type they hold very well. I used a dab of silicon in the hole to hold the magnet in place. The slots are also keyed (the 45* angle on the card is on the left) so they are always contact down and label towards you. Hit the LIKE button if you liked the design and feel free to comment also.

Magnets I used: https://www.apexmagnets.com/15mm-diameter-x-5mm-thick-disc

title: Rick's Portal Gun
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
So, for a while now I wanted a portal gun from “Rick and Morty”, because, let’s be real, who doesn’t?
I started searching Amazon to purchase one and to my surprise they weren’t any decent replicas, the one that Adult Swim endorses doesn’t look much like the one on the show. So, I focus on designs on Thingiverse. I found better results! In particular this guy https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1045661. However, after downloading and printing the design I found that firs the parts where all combine on the same file which reduces my ability to printed other than a large printer, luckily, I have access to one. second problem, the replica is just too small, like 30% smaller than it should be.
So, my reaction was simple, F***it I’m making my own. Credit to the guy above because the general dimensions a proportion for my design where taken from his original one but enlarge by around 30%, plus the strip on the top cover where really nice addition. Another modification that I made is that the design is hollow so electronics can fit inside. Hence the screw holes and the inserts hole in the main body and the other perforation for a rotatory encoder and an on/off switch.
The design its optimize for minimal support structures, no need for raft nor brim.
Hope you like it! First time uploading anything.
